File explorer — neo-tree.nvim
Maintained under the nvim-neo-tree GitHub organization (multiple maintainers, very active throughout 2025–2026). It's the most VS Code-like of the popular options — a side drawer with files, git status, and buffer/symbol views. I'd pick it over nvim-tree.lua (single-maintainer) and over oil.nvim (edits directories as text buffers — clever but unfamiliar coming from VS Code).
lua-- File explorer (VSCode-style side drawer)
vim.pack.add {
  gh 'MunifTanjim/nui.nvim',                -- dependency, must come first
  gh 'nvim-tree/nvim-web-devicons',         -- file icons
  gh 'nvim-neo-tree/neo-tree.nvim',
}
require('neo-tree').setup {
  close_if_last_window = true,
  filesystem = {
    follow_current_file   = { enabled = true },
    use_libuv_file_watcher = true,
    filtered_items = {
      visible          = false,
      hide_dotfiles    = false,   -- show .terraform, .github, etc.
      hide_gitignored  = false,   -- DevOps land — you want to see these
    },
  },
  window = { width = 32 },
}
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>fe', '<cmd>Neotree toggle<cr>', { desc = '[F]ile [E]xplorer toggle' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>fo', '<cmd>Neotree focus<cr>',  { desc = '[F]ile explorer f[O]cus' })
I used <leader>fe instead of the more common <leader>e because some kickstart versions bind <leader>e to "open floating diagnostic." If you don't have that mapping, feel free to change it.
You also need a Nerd Font installed and selected in your terminal for the icons to render. Grab one from nerdfonts.com — JetBrainsMono Nerd Font and FiraCode Nerd Font are popular safe picks.
Git — vim-fugitive (plus the gitsigns you already have)
For full git operations — :Git status, interactive staging, blame, log, diff, cherry-pick, rebase — the canonical plugin is vim-fugitive by Tim Pope. About maintenance: the README still hosts current docs and the plugin is in active use across the ecosystem. The last tagged release is older (June 2022) but that reflects maturity, not abandonment — tpope still merges fixes, and he has maintained the largest collection of vim plugins in existence for ~15 years. If anything in the vim/Neovim world is "the canonical thing everyone uses," fugitive is it for git. GitHub
lua-- Full git wrapper
vim.pack.add { gh 'tpope/vim-fugitive' }
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>gs', '<cmd>Git<cr>',                      { desc = '[G]it [S]tatus' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>gb', '<cmd>Git blame<cr>',                { desc = '[G]it [B]lame' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>gd', '<cmd>Gdiffsplit<cr>',               { desc = '[G]it [D]iff split' })
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>gl', '<cmd>Git log --oneline -n 30<cr>',  { desc = '[G]it [L]og' })
Workflow after :Git: you get a status buffer where s stages a file/hunk, u unstages, = toggles inline diff, cc commits, dv opens a vertical diff. Spend 10 minutes with :help fugitive once and it pays off forever.
If you'd rather a Magit-style modal popup UI (more discoverable, less Vim-idiomatic), the modern alternative is NeogitOrg/neogit — also actively maintained — but I'd start with fugitive because it's lighter and more battle-tested. If you want a TUI, install lazygit (brew install lazygit) and use kdheepak/lazygit.nvim to launch it inside Neovim with :LazyGit. Many DevOps folks prefer this for visual staging across many files.
Yank history — yanky.nvim
The pain it solves: you yank something, then delete something unrelated — your yank is gone, replaced by the deletion. yanky.nvim keeps a ring of recent yanks (and deletions) so you can cycle to whichever one you actually wanted.
Maintained by gbprod, an active Neovim plugin author with multiple well-maintained plugins (substitute.nvim, stay-in-place.nvim, etc.); regular releases through 2025–2026. Yanky integrates with telescope for picking from history and supports persistent storage of yanks across Neovim sessions via shada or sqlite. NeovimCraft
lua-- Yank ring + history picker
vim.pack.add { gh 'gbprod/yanky.nvim' }
require('yanky').setup {
  ring             = { storage = 'shada' },        -- persists across restarts
  system_clipboard = { sync_with_ring = true },
  highlight        = { on_put = true, on_yank = true },
}

-- Smart put + cycle through ring
vim.keymap.set({ 'n', 'x' }, 'p', '<Plug>(YankyPutAfter)')
vim.keymap.set({ 'n', 'x' }, 'P', '<Plug>(YankyPutBefore)')
vim.keymap.set('n', '<C-p>', '<Plug>(YankyPreviousEntry)')
vim.keymap.set('n', '<C-n>', '<Plug>(YankyNextEntry)')

-- Telescope-powered "search my entire yank history"
require('telescope').load_extension('yank_history')
vim.keymap.set('n', '<leader>sy', function()
  require('telescope').extensions.yank_history.yank_history({})
end, { desc = '[S]earch [Y]ank history' })
Workflow: paste with p as normal. If it pasted the wrong thing, <C-p> cycles back through previous yanks until you find the right one. <leader>sy opens a fuzzy-searchable list of every yank — cmd+shift+v on steroids.
A couple of small quality-of-life adds
nvim-surround — by kylechui, actively maintained, the modern Lua replacement for tpope's vim-surround. Lets you change/add/delete the brackets/quotes around something. cs"' turns "foo" into 'foo'. ds( deletes parens around the cursor. ysiw" wraps the current word in quotes. Trivial to install, immediately useful for editing HCL strings, JSON, YAML.
luavim.pack.add { gh 'kylechui/nvim-surround' }
require('nvim-surround').setup {}
Things you don't actually need to add: auto-pairs (Neovim has decent built-in behavior; nvim-autopairs often fights with completion — only add later if you miss it), a statusline plugin (kickstart already includes mini.statusline), and a comment plugin (Neovim 0.10+ has built-in commenting — gcc toggles the current line, gc in visual mode toggles the selection).

A practical note on verifying any of this yourself: the cheapest "is this plugin alive?" check is opening its GitHub page and looking at the dates on the most recent commits and closed issues. A plugin with commits in the last 3 months and issues being responded to is healthy regardless of star count. Anything that hasn't seen a commit in 18+ months and has open issues piling up — even if it has 5k stars — is the thing to be suspicious of.
